<bioghist encodinganalog="545">
<p>The idea for starting an "Old Ladies' Home" in Ann Arbor began on October 16, 1900 when members of the Charitable Union, a philanthropic organization, gathered together to discuss the number of elderly women with few resources who had been appealing to the organization for aid.  Mrs. W.W. Westmore of Ann Arbor was appointed president of the association responsible for raising the funds for this project, but within the year she stepped down and was succeeded by Anna Botsford Bach who helped establish and run the home for the next 15 years.</p>

<p>The home opened on November 16, 1909 with the purpose of providing "a home for older women and to conserve their health, comfort, and happiness."  In 1927 the organization moved to the historic Robert Mackenzie House which sits on four acres in West Liberty Street on Ann Arbor's Old West Side.  Operating out of this building the Anna Botsford Bach home was able to provide a home for up to sixteen women at a time.  The Home continued operating in this location until it closed in 2001.</p>

</bioghist>



<scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
<p>The Anna Botsford Bach Home record group contains materials from as early as 1909, but the bulk of the records dates to the 1990s.  The record group is divided into two series, Administrative records and Photographs.</p>
</scopecontent>

